This directory is the executable specification of `ctx-scan`'s on-disk and CLI contract: what these tests assert *is* the behavior downstream tools may rely on. Anyone changing sidecar layout, ignore-file precedence, staleness propagation, or the Stop-hook's report-only guarantee must update the corresponding test here or the change is unverified — these files, not prose docs, are the source of truth.

Both files share the same fixture pattern: a uniquely-named directory under `std::env::temp_dir()`, `remove_dir_all` before and after, and `prompts_path()` resolving `CARGO_MANIFEST_DIR`'s `../../prompts` so real prompt files back filesystem-level tests regardless of cwd. `scan.rs` additionally runs a hermetic half via `FakeFs`/`RecordingAgent` that never touches disk, used to pin exact agent-call counts against `runner::MAX_TARGETS` scope-gating — a count `stop_hook.rs` also depends on (via `MAX_TARGETS + 1` files) to assert the `--update` vs `--update --approve` escalation. Since tests aren't parallel-safe under a shared label and cleanup runs at start (not guaranteed at end if a run crashes), a new test must pick a distinct label or risk cross-test interference.

`scan.rs` owns the walk/ignore/staleness/rollup contract (`.ctxignore` seeding-then-decoupling from `.gitignore`, default excludes, exact 3-call rollup fan-out on single-file edits, orphan-leaf deletion). `stop_hook.rs` owns the separation of concerns between reporting and regeneration: stop_hook must never call `update_run` itself, must be silent on a fresh tree, and only escalates its suggested command string based on backlog size.

intent_divergence: no `intent.md` exists for this directory to check against.